===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|fa|افغان|tr=afğân||Afghan}}, from {{der|en|xbc|αβαγανο}}, first attested in the fourth century CE, most likely a compound of {{m|xbc|*apāka-|t=distant, faraway}} + {{m|xbc||tr=-āna|t=ethnic group}}: "people from a distant land".<ref>{{cite-book|chapter=On the Origin of the Terms "Afghan" & "Pashtun" (Again)|title=Studia Philologica Iranica: Gherardo Gnoli Memorial Volume|author=Johnny Cheung|editors=Enrico Morano, Elio Provasi & Adriano V. Rossi|year=2017|publisher=Scienze e Lettere|location=Rome, Italy|pages=31—51|isbn=9788866871156}}</ref> Various scholars have proposed Sanskrit etymologies since the nineteenth century (especially prior to the 2007 publication of earlier Bactrian attestations for the word), but linguist Johnny Cheung notes that these are "extremely difficult to reconcile" with recent evidence pointing to a Bactrian source.

